00:17:31,720 --> 00:17:36,160
Finally, a more front-end concept, a

539
00:17:33,960 --> 00:17:37,800
CDN, a content delivery network. So,

540
00:17:36,160 --> 00:17:39,640
what is a CDN? So, going back to a

541
00:17:37,800 --> 00:17:42,840
client-server model, imagine you are a

542
00:17:39,640 --> 00:17:44,440
client, you want to go on a website, you

543
00:17:42,840 --> 00:17:47,600
usually go to the server and get some

544
00:17:44,440 --> 00:17:49,160
static files. Static JavaScript and CSS,

545
00:17:47,600 --> 00:17:51,760
and you download that and you run that

546
00:17:49,160 --> 00:17:53,200
on your web browser. Let's imagine in a

547
00:17:51,760 --> 00:17:55,360
more hypothetical case that you are a

548
00:17:53,200 --> 00:17:57,160
user from the US and you want to visit

549
00:17:55,360 --> 00:17:59,440
the application that is based in Europe.

550
00:17:57,160 --> 00:18:01,280
For you to get the JavaScript and CSS

551
00:17:59,440 --> 00:18:03,640
and all the HTML, you have to go all the

552
00:18:01,280 --> 00:18:05,920
way to the Atlantic Ocean and come back.

553
00:18:03,640 --> 00:18:07,840
And that young trip adds latency, and

554
00:18:05,920 --> 00:18:10,200
there's no physical way you can work

555
00:18:07,840 --> 00:18:12,280
around it. No matter how performant your

556
00:18:10,200 --> 00:18:14,160
application is, there is the limit of

557
00:18:12,280 --> 00:18:16,280
the speed of light, because data only

558
00:18:14,160 --> 00:18:18,240
travels as fast as the speed of light,

559
00:18:16,280 --> 00:18:20,160
and over long distances, light is very

560
00:18:18,240 --> 00:18:23,760
fast, but it still will add around,

561
00:18:20,160 --> 00:18:26,000
let's say, 200 ms to 250 ms on every

562
00:18:23,760 --> 00:18:27,440
request of latency. So, a solution to

563
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:29,160
that is to your client decrease the

564
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:31,480
distance between you and where those

565
00:18:29,160 --> 00:18:33,200
files are hosted. And the easiest way is

566
00:18:31,480 --> 00:18:35,640
to use a content delivery network. And

567
00:18:33,200 --> 00:18:37,600
so, basically, a CDN will be a network

568
00:18:35,640 --> 00:18:39,800
of these edge locations that are placed

569
00:18:37,600 --> 00:18:41,640
all over the world, and what happens is

570
00:18:39,800 --> 00:18:43,360
that the server will push the static

571
00:18:41,640 --> 00:18:45,040
assets there, and whenever you make a

572
00:18:43,360 --> 00:18:46,680
request, you'll be redirected to the

573
00:18:45,040 --> 00:18:49,440
edge location that is closest to you.

574
00:18:46,680 --> 00:18:51,040
Now, this mechanism on how exactly are

575
00:18:49,440 --> 00:18:52,800
you getting redirected to that edge

576
00:18:51,040 --> 00:18:54,720
location that is closest to you, it's

577
00:18:52,800 --> 00:18:56,920
very interesting, and I do want to make

578
00:18:54,720 --> 00:18:58,320
a video about it, but I'm not sure if

579
00:18:56,920 --> 00:18:59,640
it's something you're interested in. If

580
00:18:58,320 --> 00:19:01,040
you want a video about it, let me know

581
00:18:59,640 --> 00:19:02,320
in the comments. It's a bit more

582
00:19:01,040 --> 00:19:04,080
technical, and it's not something you'll

583
00:19:02,320 --> 00:19:06,000
get in interviews. But, to be honest,

584
00:19:04,080 --> 00:19:07,360
it's really interesting. So, if you want

585
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:08,880
me to make a video about it, just give

586
00:19:07,360 --> 00:19:10,800
me an excuse by letting me know in the

587
00:19:08,880 --> 00:19:13,200
comments, and I'll go ahead and do that.

588
00:19:10,800 --> 00:19:15,160
Now, a CDN is a distributed cache. So,

589
00:19:13,200 --> 00:19:16,960
the technical term for whenever you get

590
00:19:15,160 --> 00:19:19,520
the asset from the CDN, it's a cache

591
00:19:16,960 --> 00:19:21,080
hit. And whenever the server pushes a

592
00:19:19,520 --> 00:19:23,320
new version, that's called cache

593
00:19:21,080 --> 00:19:25,320
invalidation. And this concept is very

594
00:19:23,320 --> 00:19:27,120
closely related to what we call cache

595
00:19:25,320 --> 00:19:30,200
busting, which is a mechanism that

596
00:19:27,120 --> 00:19:31,720
module bundles use to invalidate your

597
00:19:30,200 --> 00:19:34,200
assets. So, we make sure that when you

598
00:19:31,720 --> 00:19:35,920
deploy a new version, users really get

599
00:19:34,200 --> 00:19:37,680
the latest one, not a previous version

600
00:19:35,920 --> 00:19:40,120
that is probably still sitting somewhere

601
00:19:37,680 --> 00:19:41,440
in the CDN. I do have other videos in

602
00:19:40,120 --> 00:19:43,160
the channel talking about it, so I'm not

603
00:19:41,440 --> 00:19:44,440
going to go deep into it. But make sure

604
00:19:43,160 --> 00:19:46,280
you're able to relate those things

605
00:19:44,440 --> 00:19:48,320
across the stack. Now, keep in mind that

606
00:19:46,280 --> 00:19:49,760
a CDN is the fastest and most

607
00:19:48,320 --> 00:19:52,400
cost-effective to increase web

608
00:19:49,760 --> 00:19:53,960
performance by serving optimized assets

609
00:19:52,400 --> 00:19:56,160
with the right cache policy out of the

610
00:19:53,960 --> 00:19:58,040
box. Because nowadays, CDNs do a lot

611
00:19:56,160 --> 00:19:59,600
more than just placing the asset close

612
00:19:58,040 --> 00:20:01,920
to the client. They also compress it,

613
00:19:59,600 --> 00:20:04,120
and they also take care of the caching

614
00:20:01,920 --> 00:20:07,000
policy. So, it's a really cheap way for

615
00:20:04,120 --> 00:20:08,520
you to fix most performance problems.

616
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:10,280
Now, let's talk about design systems.

617
00:20:08,520 --> 00:20:12,320
And going back to our micro front-end

618
00:20:10,280 --> 00:20:14,040
discussions, we have a feature team,

619
00:20:12,320 --> 00:20:15,720
that's a product feature team, and then

620
00:20:14,040 --> 00:20:18,360
we might have the payments feature team,

621
00:20:15,720 --> 00:20:20,480
and they work separately and release

622
00:20:18,360 --> 00:20:22,560
independently. Those are completely

623
00:20:20,480 --> 00:20:23,920
separate product teams. And the problem

624
00:20:22,560 --> 00:20:26,360
there is that you might get code

625
00:20:23,920 --> 00:20:28,440
repetition or what we call visual

626
00:20:26,360 --> 00:20:30,880
divergence. You can have this silos

627
00:20:28,440 --> 00:20:32,160
mentality. And so, basically, a button

628
00:20:30,880 --> 00:20:34,080
in the product page will look

629
00:20:32,160 --> 00:20:35,680
differently than a button on the payment

630
00:20:34,080 --> 00:20:37,640
page. And so, you will lose what we call

631
00:20:35,680 --> 00:20:39,200
visual coherence, and people will start

632
00:20:37,640 --> 00:20:40,800
to notice that those are actually

633
00:20:39,200 --> 00:20:43,640
separate front-ends because they look

634
00:20:40,800 --> 00:20:45,200
differently. And that's not good from a

635
00:20:43,640 --> 00:20:46,600
product perspective, but it's also not

636
00:20:45,200 --> 00:20:48,440
good from a technical perspective

637
00:20:46,600 --> 00:20:49,880
because you have too much repeated code.

638
00:20:48,440 --> 00:20:51,360
And so, the solution is to have a design

639
00:20:49,880 --> 00:20:52,840
system. And in a design system, the

640
00:20:51,360 --> 00:20:55,640
first thing you do is to define your

641
00:20:52,840 --> 00:20:57,120
design tokens. That's basically your

642
00:20:55,640 --> 00:20:59,840
team information. What's your primary

643
00:20:57,120 --> 00:21:02,120
color, what is your border definition,

644
00:20:59,840 --> 00:21:04,240
your fonts families, and so on and so

645
00:21:02,120 --> 00:21:07,000
forth. And the modern way to do that is

646
00:21:04,240 --> 00:21:09,120
you add them as CSS custom properties,

647
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:11,120
basically variables, at the global level

648
00:21:09,120 --> 00:21:13,720
in your CSS, probably in the shell micro

649
00:21:11,120 --> 00:21:15,200
front end, and then it gets fed into all

650
00:21:13,720 --> 00:21:16,840
the other micro front ends. But, you can

651
00:21:15,200 --> 00:21:18,560
go a bit farther and build reusable

652
00:21:16,840 --> 00:21:21,440
components that then the feature teams

653
00:21:18,560 --> 00:21:23,840
can use to assemble their features. So,

654
00:21:21,440 --> 00:21:25,240
you could build inputs and buttons, and

655
00:21:23,840 --> 00:21:26,800
basically they would consume that UI

656
00:21:25,240 --> 00:21:28,360
package and use it in all these

657
00:21:26,800 --> 00:21:29,720
different micro front ends. So,

658
00:21:28,360 --> 00:21:32,240
basically what you achieve is that the

659
00:21:29,720 --> 00:21:33,920
UI looks consistent, but also you don't

660
00:21:32,240 --> 00:21:35,440
repeat your code. The cool thing about

661
00:21:33,920 --> 00:21:37,360
the design system is you can take care

662
00:21:35,440 --> 00:21:39,600
of accessibility, you can have all those

663
00:21:37,360 --> 00:21:41,080
components unit tested, and basically

664
00:21:39,600 --> 00:21:44,120
you are applying at an architectural

665
00:21:41,080 --> 00:21:46,840
level the do not repeat yourself dry

666
00:21:44,120 --> 00:21:48,600
principle. And going back to AI coding,

667
00:21:46,840 --> 00:21:50,040
a solid design system really makes the

668
00:21:48,600 --> 00:21:52,720
difference between generating some

669
00:21:50,040 --> 00:21:54,720
component slob and having inconsistent

670
00:21:52,720 --> 00:21:56,960
styles and bugs that need a lot of

671
00:21:54,720 --> 00:21:59,640
rework, and really having a consistent,

672
00:21:56,960 --> 00:22:01,240
reliable coding agent output. Trust me,

673
00:21:59,640 --> 00:22:02,640
I've been building a lot of AI in the

674
00:22:01,240 --> 00:22:04,640
last couple of months, and the first

675
00:22:02,640 --> 00:22:06,200
thing I do when I make a new project is

676
00:22:04,640 --> 00:22:08,600
to tell to extract from whatever the

677
00:22:06,200 --> 00:22:11,080
design is the design system, because

678
00:22:08,600 --> 00:22:13,000
then you feed that into your coding

679
00:22:11,080 --> 00:22:14,960
agent through different sessions, and

680
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:16,800
you still get consistent output. If you

681
00:22:14,960 --> 00:22:18,800
don't do that, the agent will make

682
00:22:16,800 --> 00:22:20,320
things up, and your UI would just look

683
00:22:18,800 --> 00:22:22,200
different, and it'll be obvious that it

684
00:22:20,320 --> 00:22:24,600
was live coded. Now, our next concept is

685
00:22:22,200 --> 00:22:26,680
a design to code MCP, that's a model

686
00:22:24,600 --> 00:22:28,000
context protocol server. And so,

687
00:22:26,680 --> 00:22:29,720
basically, you remember we have our

688
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:31,520
design system, and normally you would

689
00:22:29,720 --> 00:22:33,040
import that to start building with it.

690
00:22:31,520 --> 00:22:34,960
But, nowadays, let's imagine that your

691
00:22:33,040 --> 00:22:37,240
designers built your design system

692
00:22:34,960 --> 00:22:38,840
initially in Figma, and then you

693
00:22:37,240 --> 00:22:41,680
implement it in your library. You can

694
00:22:38,840 --> 00:22:45,080
use the Figma MCP server with a coding

695
00:22:41,680 --> 00:22:46,520
agent to very quickly assemble features

696
00:22:45,080 --> 00:22:48,280
into the feature teams, into the

697
00:22:46,520 --> 00:22:49,720
vertical slices of your product. And

698
00:22:48,280 --> 00:22:51,800
this is the kind of workflow that most

699
00:22:49,720 --> 00:22:53,560
companies are moving towards. So, if you

700
00:22:51,800 --> 00:22:55,760
are a front end engineer, you got to

701
00:22:53,560 --> 00:22:57,760
make sure that you know how to use an

702
00:22:55,760 --> 00:23:00,120
MCP server, you know what an MCP server

703
00:22:57,760 --> 00:23:02,200
is, and ideally, whatever design tool

704
00:23:00,120 --> 00:23:03,840
your team is using, you can plug an MCP

705
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:06,640
into that or you might have to even

706
00:23:03,840 --> 00:23:08,840
build that connection yourself. And then

707
00:23:06,640 --> 00:23:10,520
plug that into your AI coding agent like

708
00:23:08,840 --> 00:23:13,360
Cloud Code, which is the most used in

709
00:23:10,520 --> 00:23:15,960
enterprise or Codex. Now, a quick note

710
00:23:13,360 --> 00:23:17,400
on CSS architecture and design tokens.

711
00:23:15,960 --> 00:23:19,040
What you can do to take things even

712
00:23:17,400 --> 00:23:21,520
further is to apply the Atomic CSS

713
00:23:19,040 --> 00:23:23,320
methodology and with your design tokens,

714
00:23:21,520 --> 00:23:25,000
create atomic classes that you can use

715
00:23:23,320 --> 00:23:26,560
in your code base. So, basically, you

716
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:28,800
define what the border would be, but

717
00:23:26,560 --> 00:23:30,720
then you create a dot border class that

718
00:23:28,800 --> 00:23:32,520
has that property. And then the only

719
00:23:30,720 --> 00:23:34,360
thing that other developers have to do

720
00:23:32,520 --> 00:23:37,120
is to use that class. And this is how

721
00:23:34,360 --> 00:23:40,200
Tailwind CSS works. So, keep this in

722
00:23:37,120 --> 00:23:43,120
mind. Tailwind CSS is an implementation

723
00:23:40,200 --> 00:23:45,000
of the Atomic CSS architecture style for

724
00:23:43,120 --> 00:23:46,960
CSS. And there's three more

725
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:49,280
architectural styles, which I won't get

726
00:23:46,960 --> 00:23:51,200
into right now, but who knows, maybe

727
00:23:49,280 --> 00:23:53,000
I'll make a video about it later on.

728
00:23:51,200 --> 00:23:55,240
Next front end system design concept,

729
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:56,560
the monorepo. So, basically, our

730
00:23:55,240 --> 00:23:58,040
applications right now are sitting in

731
00:23:56,560 --> 00:24:00,040
all these different repos where you have

732
00:23:58,040 --> 00:24:01,800
a GitHub repo for the shell, one for the

733
00:24:00,040 --> 00:24:04,000
payment micro front end, inventory micro

734
00:24:01,800 --> 00:24:06,320
front end, and it's all spread out into

735
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:07,800
thousands of repos. And the problem

736
00:24:06,320 --> 00:24:09,320
there is that you end up with different

737
00:24:07,800 --> 00:24:10,840
code styles, different dependencies, and

738
00:24:09,320 --> 00:24:12,600
different quality standards. Some people

739
00:24:10,840 --> 00:24:14,960
might be using TypeScript, they might be

740
00:24:12,600 --> 00:24:16,800
using different linter configurations,

741
00:24:14,960 --> 00:24:19,440
and it's so easy to have what we call

742
00:24:16,800 --> 00:24:21,600
architectural drift or code style drift

743
00:24:19,440 --> 00:24:22,800
where two projects diverge too much.

744
00:24:21,600 --> 00:24:24,720
What's the problem with that? If you're

745
00:24:22,800 --> 00:24:27,000
a developer and you change teams, you

746
00:24:24,720 --> 00:24:29,280
